# ETL Manual Jobs And Existing-Item Checks

## Manual job types

The local ETL UI and manual trigger endpoints support these single-job runs:

- `tv`
- `movie`
- `person`
- `podcast`
- `book`

The CLI runner in `src/etl/run_nightly_etl.py` must keep the same job vocabulary when `--job` is used.

## Resume window semantics

Manual and scheduled ETL windows are day-based.

- `start_date` and `end_date` are treated as the requested TMDB changes window.
- The next automatic start date is `last_successful_run + 1 day`.
- If a job last completed on `2026-03-12`, the next run should begin on `2026-03-13`, not re-run `2026-03-12`.

## TMDB existing-item checks

The TMDB changes ETL must not scan the entire Redis keyspace to decide whether a changed item already exists.

- Do **not** build a startup `set[int]` by `SCAN`ning `media:*`.
- Do **not** assume bare TMDB numeric IDs are globally unique across movie and TV.
- Existing-item checks must use the typed Redis media key shape:
  - movie: `media:tmdb_movie_{tmdb_id}`
  - tv: `media:tmdb_tv_{tmdb_id}`
- Prefer pipelined per-batch `EXISTS` checks over any full-keyspace scan.

Reasoning:

- movie and TV TMDB IDs can collide
- the Redis key shape is MCID-based and media-type-qualified
- batch point lookups scale with the TMDB changes result set, while `SCAN` scales with the whole Redis dataset

## Existing-item filter behavior

If a changed TMDB item already exists in Redis, it should bypass the new-item media filter and be re-indexed.

This rule exists so updates to already indexed titles are not skipped just because the title would no longer pass the insertion filter.

## Timestamp-preserving upserts

Person ETL and bestseller-author ETL writes should preserve Redis document timestamps.

- Read the existing JSON document before overwrite.
- Use `resolve_timestamps(...)` to keep `created_at` stable and refresh `modified_at`.
- Batch this as read-before-write pipelines rather than blind overwrites.
